---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import PageHero from '../components/PageHero.astro';
import FooterStrip from '../components/FooterStrip.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import SiteCtaBand from '../components/SiteCtaBand.astro';
import ContentSection from '../components/ContentSection.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Vepoloxamer | The Science">
  <SiteHeader />
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="Section 02 — The Science"
    title="The Core Mechanism of Action:<br><em>Why Vepoloxamer Can Go Where Other Drugs Cannot</em>"
    intro="Most therapeutics are designed around a single receptor, enzyme, or pathway. Vepoloxamer operates at a more fundamental level — the cellular membrane itself. Its core mechanism of action gives it two distinct and valuable clinical windows: it can be deployed before an insult to protect healthy cells from anticipated damage, or immediately after an insult to limit the cascade of secondary injury that follows."
  />

  <ContentSection
    eyebrow="The Science"
    subtitle="The Core Mechanism of Action"
    intro="Published science points to a multi-mechanistic therapeutic profile rather than a single narrow receptor story."
  >
    <div class="grid grid-3">
      <article class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">
          <svg width="56" height="44" viewBox="0 0 56 44" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-label="Lipid bilayer">
            <circle cx="8" cy="7" r="4" fill="#2E7DC4" />
            <circle cx="20" cy="7" r="4" fill="#2E7DC4" />
            <circle cx="32" cy="7" r="4" fill="#2E7DC4" />
            <circle cx="44" cy="7" r="4" fill="#2E7DC4" />
            <line x1="8" y1="11" x2="8" y2="21" stroke="#1B4F8A" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" />
            <line x1="20" y1="11" x2="20" y2="21" stroke="#1B4F8A" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" />
            <line x1="32" y1="11" x2="32" y2="21" stroke="#1B4F8A" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" />
            <line x1="44" y1="11" x2="44" y2="21" stroke="#1B4F8A" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" />
            <rect x="2" y="21" width="52" height="2" fill="#A8CBE8" opacity="0.35" rx="1" />
            <line x1="8" y1="23" x2="8" y2="33" stroke="#1B4F8A" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" />
            <line x1="20" y1="23" x2="20" y2="33" stroke="#1B4F8A" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" />
            <line x1="32" y1="23" x2="32" y2="33" stroke="#1B4F8A" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" />
            <line x1="44" y1="23" x2="44" y2="33" stroke="#1B4F8A" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" />
            <circle cx="8" cy="37" r="4" fill="#2E7DC4" />
            <circle cx="20" cy="37" r="4" fill="#2E7DC4" />
            <circle cx="32" cy="37" r="4" fill="#2E7DC4" />
            <circle cx="44" cy="37" r="4" fill="#2E7DC4" />
            <path d="M52 4 Q58 22 52 40" stroke="#C9A84C" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="3 2" fill="none" opacity="0.7" />
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h3 class="card-title">Membrane Stabilization</h3>
        <p>Integrates with and stabilizes damaged cell membranes via its hydrophobic central block, reducing leakage and preserving cellular integrity under stress.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">⚡</div>
        <h3 class="card-title">Free Radical Scavenging</h3>
        <p>Pairs radicalized electrons, inhibiting propagation of oxidative inflammatory cascades that drive secondary tissue destruction after an initial injury event.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔥</div>
        <h3 class="card-title">Anti-Inflammatory Signaling</h3>
        <p>Inhibits activation of inflammatory pathways downstream of membrane damage, reducing tissue injury across contexts from mucositis to cardiac ischemia to traumatic brain injury.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔬</div>
        <h3 class="card-title">Intracellular Engagement</h3>
        <p>Emerging research demonstrates that Vepoloxamer is not limited to surface membrane interaction and may also modulate downstream intracellular repair pathways.</p>
        <a class="pub-link" href="#">Alatrash et al. (2025): Active transport of P188 in brain endothelial cells for cellular repair</a>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">💨</div>
        <h3 class="card-title">Nitric Oxide–Mediated Cardioprotection</h3>
        <p>A 2025 study published in Scientific Reports demonstrated that P188's cardioprotective effects are mediated through increased endothelial nitric oxide production.</p>
        <a class="pub-link" href="#">Chen et al. (2025) and Li et al. (2025)</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </ContentSection>

  <ContentSection
    eyebrow="The Science"
    subtitle="Prophylactic Shield or Acute Rescue Agent"
    intro="Because the molecule acts at the membrane and downstream injury-cascade level, it can plausibly fit both planned-insult and post-insult clinical settings."
  >
    <div class="grid" style="grid-template-columns: 1fr;">
      <article class="moa-box">
        <div class="scenario">Example: Radiation Therapy for Head & Neck Cancer</div>
        <h3 class="card-title" style="color: var(--ice);">Mode 1: Prophylactic — Before the Insult</h3>
        <p>If Vepoloxamer is on board prior to radiation delivery, it inserts into healthy cell membranes and protects them from the oxidative and inflammatory cascade triggered by ionizing radiation.</p>
        <div class="embed-note">
          Diagram placeholder: <strong>vepoloxamer_radiation_timeline.html</strong><br />
          The notes suggest this should likely stack with the copy or open in a modal on a future refinement pass.
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="moa-box">
        <div class="scenario">Example: STEMI & Reperfusion Injury</div>
        <h3 class="card-title" style="color: var(--ice);">Mode 2: Acute Rescue — After the Insult</h3>
        <p>Vepoloxamer administered at the moment of reperfusion can attenuate damage by sealing compromised cardiomyocyte membranes and dampening the inflammatory cascade before it propagates.</p>
        <div class="outcome" style="background: rgba(201,168,76,0.12); color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); border-left-color: var(--gold);">
          The same acute rescue mechanism applies to ischemic stroke and TBI, where secondary injury drives much of the long-term damage.
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>

    <blockquote class="quote quote--indented">
      “Vepoloxamer is an amphipathic triblock copolymer with multi-mechanistic properties believed to improve these pathophysiologic consequences, by sealing damaged cell membranes and inhibiting hydrophobic cellular adhesive interactions.”
      <cite>— White, Hines, Liu et al., Blood (2015)</cite>
    </blockquote>
  </ContentSection>

  <ContentSection
    eyebrow="The Science"
    subtitle="Why Multi-Indication Reach Is Scientifically Logical"
    intro="Oxidative stress, membrane damage, and inflammatory cascades are shared endpoints across many diseases and injuries. The platform breadth follows from the mechanism."
  >
    <div class="embed-note">
      Diagram placeholder: <strong>vepoloxamer_hub_spoke_diagram_v4.html</strong><br />
      The notes suggest this may also be a modal candidate in a future UI pass.
    </div>

    <div class="band" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
      <h2 class="section-title">50 Years of Science — And a Purification That Changes Everything</h2>
      <p>
        Commercial poloxamer 188 is a mixed polymer population with batch-to-batch variability. An early
        key discovery was that low-molecular-weight impurities present in commercial-grade P-188 were
        responsible for dose-limiting renal toxicity — and that removing them through a proprietary
        purification process enabled the higher therapeutic doses required for efficacy.
      </p>
    </div>
  </ContentSection>

  <SiteCtaBand
    title="Mechanism is where the platform story begins."
    body="The science page establishes why the same molecule can logically map to multiple clinical windows and therapeutic areas."
    primaryHref="/preclinical/"
    primaryLabel="See the Evidence"
    secondaryHref="/partner/"
    secondaryLabel="Contact Us"
  />

  <SiteFooter />
  <FooterStrip />
</BaseLayout>
